RMarkdown introduction

Dan Olner

Working with RMarkdown

RMarkdown 1: RStudios own example / looking at the reference guide

Well use RMarkdown for preparing assignments. Its a way to write reports and run code together that can output to Microsoft Word, PDF (or HTML as well for opening in a browser). Well use either Word or PDF output. Its also a super-useful tool for making reproducible quantitative social science.

Lets look at the RMarkdown example that RStudio provides you with.

  1. Open whatever RStudio project youre working with, if you dont have it open already.
  2. Go to file / new file / RMarkdown
  3. Give the file a name (just something like test) and set the author to your own name, if it isnt already. Also, choose an output option (choose Word for now, though we can decide later what we want.)

Note: the first time you do this, RStudio might prompt you to install some new libraries. Let it install them.

Select OK, then we should have our new RMarkdown file. Go to file/save to save it, or use CTRL + S (or CMD + S on macs).

You should now have an example RMarkdown file. These have the file extension .Rmd (as compared to just .R for normal R scripts.)

Lets look through what weve got there:

  • A header enclosed on each side by three dashes and some setup script. You can leave those alone, though if you want to change names and dates, you can.
  • A document heading preceded by two hash symbols. (Thats a level 2 heading, more on that shortly.)
  • Some text, with some formatting. (The text handily explains more about RMarkdown.)
  • A code chunk that starts ```{r}. It has the word cars after r, but thats just a label for the code chunk, you dont need it.

The important thing to know:

  • The text will output as text, as youd get in a Word document
  • The code will run and output what it produces to the document (unless you ask it not to, more on that in a moment).

So lets just try outputting this sample document and see what happens.

Look for the knit button at the top of the window. Theres a down symbol on the right of it - click that. You should see the following:

Lets select Word first and see if that works. If you havent saved the Rmd script yet, itll prompt you to save it now. Then it should run through the script in the RMarkdown tab next to the console, before opening the Word document for you to check over.

Assuming that worked, lets also try outputting as PDF. Repeat the last step but choose PDF instead.

I think Mac installations can automatically output to PDF without any additional steps. Windows users may need to take an extra step (and possibly Mac users too, though my machine was fine.) If PDF isnt working, we may need to do a couple more installation steps.

If PDF isnt working yet, type these into the console (do not include in your R script, you dont want them running more than once). Note, thats two colons after tinytex in the 2nd line: that just saves us having to load the package with library(tinytex).

install.packages('tinytex')
tinytex::install_tinytex()

Once those have run, try outputting the RMarkdown to PDF again.

Fingers crossed that worked and you now have a Word and/or PDF document of the sample RMarkdown. Youll see, the code has run and output to the document.

To see how to format in RMarkdown, go to Help / RMarkdown reference guide. Lets look through some of whats on that page. Youll only need the first two sections on Markdown syntax and chunk options. In Markdown syntax:

  • Details on how to format text
  • Including how to set headings with the hash symbol (one hash for a top level heading, two hashes for level 2 etc)
  • How to make numbered and non-numbered lists
  • And a bunch of other formatting options - have a look through them and use whats useful.
  • Note theres an inline equation format too, if you need that.

In the next section, there are some options for the R code chunks. You may not need any of these, but its worth knowing theyre there. Some of the most important:

  • It explains the basic R code chunk: three backticks and the letter r in curly braces opens the code chunk and three more backticks closes it. The back tick on my Mac is to the left of the Z key and on Windows machines its below escape.
  • or you can just go to code/insert chunk in the menu. (Theres a shortcut key too though it never works on my Windows machines.)
  • As the reference guide shows, code chunk options go inside the curly braces, like this:

You may never need to use code chunks, but they are sometimes useful. Heres a couple from the reference worth knowing about:

  • Eval: if set to false, the code wont run but it will display in your document. Thats useful if you want to show some code off but not have R run it.
  • Echo: if false, the code will run, but the code itself wont be displayed in the document. You probably dont want this, as I want to see all the code youre running in the assignments.

Theres another useful option to avoid having messy outputs. By default, RMarkdown outputs everything from the code. So , for example, imagine if wed made a vector of random numbers. If we included code to output the vector (the lone x here), the chunk would look like this:

And in the document here, wed get this:

x <- runif(10)
x
##  [1] 0.5199414 0.8342395 0.6282855 0.5190492 0.7580811 0.8658702 0.5200105
##  [8] 0.5586398 0.9837288 0.7280619

But if that was, say, ten thousand random numbers, we really wouldnt want to output them all. We can tell R to not do the output like this:

Note: you can run code within the code chunks just as you would in a normal R script. And thats often a useful thing to do when youre testing code as you make an RMarkdown document. But RStudios default behaviour is odd: itll output the result on the script page itself (inline results). You may or may not like this - a lot of people hate it - so if you want to stop that happening and have output go to the console as normal, do the following:

  • Go to Tools / Global options
  • Select the RMarkdown tab
  • Turn off show output inline for all RMarkdown documents
